# Backend Architecture Overview

>The backend of the web application is designed using a containerized approach powered by **Docker**. It integrates several key components to ensure modularity, scalability, and maintainability:

Docker services:
* **Flask** (Framework)
* **Apache** (Server/Proxy)
* **Mysql** (Database)

>**Flask**: Serves as the primary backend framework. It handles:
>* Routing
>* API Endpoints
>* User Authentication
>* Business Logic

 The reason for its use is mainly due to priorities. Our goal for this project is to create an artificial intelligence-powered web application which displays the movement data of a person who wears the Hipper device. Incorporating AI into this project is a challenge as it has not been done before. There is no documentation and no premade dataset, therefore it will take some time to get everything prepared and ready for training. The uncertainty of the speed of our progression in this field led us to go with a familiar back-end technology, so that we can be certain that there will be enough time for us to develop a capable AI model.

>**Apache**: Acts as a **reverse proxy** and **web server**, forwarding client requests to the Flask application via **mod_wsgi**.

>**MySQL**: A relational database system used to store and manage user data, movement progress records, and any other application-specific information.

